    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "THE VOICE SPECIFICALLY "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Flip-tongue style rap (in Jamaica) is doubling the syllabic syncopation in the manner of dancehall DJs"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Underground MCs flows tend to closely resemble dancehall's sing-song,s taccato, double-time, end-rhyme orientation. They also have adapted DJs frequent disregard for conventional key relationships. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The underground recordings supported a youth- and class-inflected cultural politics of Blackness and did so significantly by embracing (if not amplifying) the Nuyorican dimensions of Puerto Rican culture. "
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
